AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]?

00:36:19.430 --> 00:36:20.980
THERESE CAOUETTE: OK, just let
me repeat it for the people

00:36:20.980 --> 00:36:21.620
are listening in.

00:36:21.620 --> 00:36:26.590
She was asking why is it that
people don't identify with the

00:36:26.590 --> 00:36:27.780
word trafficking?

00:36:27.780 --> 00:36:29.450
Is it the experience
of trafficking

00:36:29.450 --> 00:36:30.990
itself or just the word?

00:36:30.990 --> 00:36:32.240
Is that pretty much--

00:36:32.240 --> 00:36:34.400
so I would say that it's
a little bit of both.

00:36:34.400 --> 00:36:36.800
They don't have that word, of
course, in their vocabulary,

00:36:36.800 --> 00:36:37.830
so that doesn't make sense.

00:36:37.830 --> 00:36:41.460
And if you if you translate it,
it doesn't really work.

00:36:41.460 --> 00:36:43.620
But they also don't
have the concept.

00:36:43.620 --> 00:36:47.900
I mean if anybody have been
fortune of to travel in some

00:36:47.900 --> 00:36:51.740
of these really remote areas,
the trust and the kindness,

00:36:51.740 --> 00:36:56.620
the generosity is so amazing
that they just don't believe

00:36:56.620 --> 00:37:00.770
people would take advantage
of anybody to that extent.

00:37:00.770 --> 00:37:02.240
I think they really
fundamentally

00:37:02.240 --> 00:37:03.340
don't believe that.

00:37:03.340 --> 00:37:06.510
They wouldn't have it
in their world view.

00:37:06.510 --> 00:37:08.860
But even when they
face migration--

00:37:08.860 --> 00:37:10.190
then I think that there's
another issue.

00:37:10.190 --> 00:37:12.910
When it does happen there's so
much shame, especially for the

00:37:12.910 --> 00:37:14.960
girls, that when they
come back they would

00:37:14.960 --> 00:37:16.530
never talk about it.

00:37:16.530 --> 00:37:19.020
So it perpetuates that cycle.

00:37:19.020 --> 00:37:21.320
When you talk about
vulnerabilities it's a little

00:37:21.320 --> 00:37:22.930
bit less personal.

00:37:22.930 --> 00:37:25.310
It happens to everybody
in different contexts.

00:37:25.310 --> 00:37:27.540
So people feel a little bit more
comfortable to talk about

00:37:27.540 --> 00:37:30.390
the vulnerabilities of other
people, maybe not of

00:37:30.390 --> 00:37:31.950
themselves.

00:37:31.950 --> 00:37:34.040
But even in that context
I just don't feel that

00:37:34.040 --> 00:37:37.020
trafficking, and certainly
the trafficking--

00:37:37.020 --> 00:37:39.080
because we ourselves don't even
know what we're talking

00:37:39.080 --> 00:37:40.600
when we use that word.

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:43.780
They themselves also are
very confused by it.

00:37:43.780 --> 00:37:45.650
But migration is much
more concrete.

00:37:45.650 --> 00:37:48.250
People are moving, there are
risks, things happen.

00:37:48.250 --> 00:37:51.000
It's much more concrete--

00:37:51.000 --> 00:37:54.090
obvious-- to them what
we're talking about.

00:37:54.090 --> 00:37:55.780
So it's a combination of the
two, I guess is what I'm

00:37:55.780 --> 00:37:58.330
trying to say.

00:37:58.330 --> 00:37:59.426
Yes please.

00:37:59.426 --> 00:38:01.410
AUDIENCE: I really loved hearing
about [INAUDIBLE]?

00:38:21.780 --> 00:38:22.950
THERESE CAOUETTE: Yes.

00:38:22.950 --> 00:38:24.220
She's asking about--

00:38:24.220 --> 00:38:26.750
education is great, but
then there's a void.

00:38:26.750 --> 00:38:30.320
There's a lack of jobs that
people face when they actually

00:38:30.320 --> 00:38:33.700
do finish school, or
become literate.

00:38:33.700 --> 00:38:35.610
And I think that's very
much a reality.

00:38:35.610 --> 00:38:39.710
I think the whole effort to do
livelihoods and try to work

00:38:39.710 --> 00:38:44.430
with women and find other
alternative to employment is

00:38:44.430 --> 00:38:45.690
very critical.

00:38:45.690 --> 00:38:48.060
And I think that there are
opportunities, people are

00:38:48.060 --> 00:38:49.230
working on it.

00:38:49.230 --> 00:38:51.610
The infrastructure
of the new roads.

00:38:51.610 --> 00:38:53.320
These are the positive
things of that.

00:38:53.320 --> 00:38:54.620
It's bringing more jobs.

00:38:54.620 --> 00:38:57.390
It's bringing a way to
sell their produce.

00:38:57.390 --> 00:38:58.460
It's bringing markets.

00:38:58.460 --> 00:39:01.970
You see people in remote areas
on this last trip sewing

00:39:01.970 --> 00:39:04.530
handbags, things that they
can sell in the market.

00:39:04.530 --> 00:39:06.420
That wasn't there before.

00:39:06.420 --> 00:39:09.820
So the development of the
infrastructure isn't only bad,

00:39:09.820 --> 00:39:11.170
it just brings new dynamics.

00:39:11.170 --> 00:39:14.900
And some of the positive parts
of it does bring new markets.

00:39:14.900 --> 00:39:18.720
So yes, that's an ongoing
challenge and there are

00:39:18.720 --> 00:39:21.450
ongoing struggles to
try to find ways

00:39:21.450 --> 00:39:22.700
that they can be employed.

00:39:28.490 --> 00:39:29.090
Yes, please.

